WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.639
Hey there, welcome to the POSIT Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:22.000
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.240
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.320
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:42.360
Can't wait to see you there. I'm just really super excited to introduce our featured leader

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:48.320
today, Keith McNulty, Analytics Leader at McKinsey & Company. Keith, welcome. Will you

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:53.880
let us tell us a little bit about yourself, what you do, what you like to do for fun?

00:00:54.880 --> 00:01:00.200
Yeah, thanks, Libby, and thank you guys for inviting me. It's a lot of fun to spend an

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:09.400
hour speaking with such a diverse and interesting community here. Yeah, my name is Keith McNulty.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:16.480
I kind of navigated a path into the data science world in what's probably a little unusual

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:20.040
a way. I think nowadays people are coming into data science having done some sort of

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:26.279
data science-related qualification, whereas I started out as a mathematician. I then went

00:01:26.279 --> 00:01:33.639
into management consulting. I then moved into psychometrics, which is a fascinating field

00:01:33.639 --> 00:01:39.480
which I still am very involved in, and the study of employee behavior and how it affects

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:46.239
the workplace. And then about maybe seven years ago, I caught the data science bug and

00:01:46.239 --> 00:01:52.279
decided to retrain myself as a data scientist, built a team at my employer, which is now

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:58.440
a fairly large team that kind of focuses on the applications of analytics to solving questions

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:05.160
related to people and talent. And in terms of what I like to do for fun, I mean, I just

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:11.119
love engaging with the open source community. It's how one of the reasons why I've managed

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:16.199
to have a lot of success in my current career is because of the contributions of a lot of

00:02:16.199 --> 00:02:20.240
open source individuals and the fact that I've been able to take advantage of that and

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:24.440
my team has been able to take advantage of that. So I believe a lot in giving back. So

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:29.880
I spend a lot of time developing materials and publishing open source books and things

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:34.119
like that to make sure that things that I've learned are passed on appropriately to other

00:02:34.119 --> 00:02:39.440
people so they can take advantage of that as well. And I think, you know, for me, one

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:44.520
of the things that attracts me to working in this space is the amazing open source community

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:51.399
and the way people like help each other. So that's something that, you know, I'm happy

00:02:51.399 --> 00:02:54.880
to talk more about today, but it's definitely the thing that attracts me to working in this

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:55.880
field.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:04.279
I mean, same. The people are the biggest differentiator for me, no matter where I go or what I'm doing.

00:03:04.279 --> 00:03:11.800
I first learned about you via LinkedIn. You're very active on LinkedIn. Were you that active

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.679
before you were in data science? Were you like already out there spreading knowledge,

00:03:16.679 --> 00:03:21.440
writing books, doing all the things that you do? That sort of like, oh, there's a big community

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:24.479
here and there's a place where I can connect.

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:28.600
I certainly wasn't very active before I got involved in data science. I think part of

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:35.279
that is because my involvement in data science kind of coincided with when LinkedIn became

00:03:35.279 --> 00:03:43.399
more of a social network. But certainly, you know, there was this very exciting period

00:03:43.399 --> 00:03:49.600
on LinkedIn, probably between 2016 and 2018, where people were discovering a lot of this

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:54.080
tooling for the first time, lots of people. And there was a huge amount of sharing of

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:59.000
kind of open source knowledge. And a lot of that happened on Twitter as well during

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.199
that period. And so, you know, one of the reasons, one of the things I try to do is

00:04:05.199 --> 00:04:10.360
keep that going. I think, unfortunately, LinkedIn has become a bit more salesy and a little

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:15.839
bit more, you know, it's kind of its culture has changed a little bit since that time.

00:04:15.839 --> 00:04:19.480
But I certainly personally try to keep that spirit going and making sure that like what

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:23.260
I share there is useful to people and, you know, that it's something they can take away

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:25.019
with them and potentially use themselves.

00:04:26.619 --> 00:04:30.739
Well, it's definitely changed, for sure, since I started using it, I think the first time

00:04:30.739 --> 00:04:36.420
I was forced to use LinkedIn was in undergrad, I was forced to create a LinkedIn account,

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:39.779
someone made me use it. And I thought, what is this thing? I'm never going to use this

00:04:39.779 --> 00:04:44.980
ever again. And now I'm on it all the time. And I have found it to be a social network.

00:04:44.980 --> 00:04:48.899
And if you curate your feed the right way, it can be pretty nice.

00:04:49.899 --> 00:04:54.820
Well, I already have some questions popping up in Slido, which I feel like never happens

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:58.899
this early. So let's go ahead and hop over to Slido.

00:04:58.899 --> 00:05:02.059
I will sacrifice some of my selfish questions I wanted to ask Keith.

00:05:02.059 --> 00:05:04.940
I bet somebody is going to ask them in Slido, so that's OK.

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:09.820
Tony, you asked a question and I don't see an asterisk.

00:05:10.459 --> 00:05:13.739
Tony DiPesa, are you able to answer that?

00:05:13.739 --> 00:05:15.179
And did I say your last name right?

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:17.140
Close. DiPesa.

00:05:17.779 --> 00:05:19.299
DiPesa. Sorry, Tony.

00:05:19.299 --> 00:05:20.500
No, no worries.

00:05:21.859 --> 00:05:27.380
In Italian, it's probably different, but that's the Americanized version.

00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:33.619
So, hi, Keith. Thanks for sharing your information today.

00:05:33.619 --> 00:05:36.100
I was just wondering if you could maybe talk a little bit about

00:05:37.779 --> 00:05:43.220
your most favorite resources that you used while retraining yourself as a data scientist.

00:05:44.179 --> 00:05:49.459
Things that seem to be the most helpful or most enjoyable, engaging.

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:55.220
It's a great question, Tony, and I'm not sure my answer would necessarily

00:05:57.619 --> 00:06:01.940
align with how people would retrain themselves today.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:07.380
And the reason I say that is because I retrained in 2016,

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:14.019
and there was a significant limit to the amount of public information that was available

00:06:14.019 --> 00:06:18.980
at that time in terms of example code, how you might get something done

00:06:20.019 --> 00:06:22.500
if you want to achieve a particular task with your code.

00:06:23.619 --> 00:06:28.899
And what I found was that the learning during that period for me

00:06:28.899 --> 00:06:31.059
was in a huge amount of trial and error.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:35.700
So I'd write code and I'd just watch it fail.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:40.420
And then I would dig into Stack Overflow and some of those kind of resources that date back

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:42.420
quite a while to try and work out how it failed.

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:44.179
And sometimes I wouldn't be able to find the answer,

00:06:44.739 --> 00:06:50.500
and I would just keep changing my code until eventually it worked.

00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:52.980
And then I'd realize why it worked.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:56.980
And that type of process was a huge part of the learning for me

00:06:57.619 --> 00:06:59.619
to get underneath why your code works.

00:07:00.739 --> 00:07:04.100
And of course, the resources that got me started are the resources

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:05.459
that a lot of people still rely on today.

00:07:05.459 --> 00:07:06.420
I started out in R.

00:07:07.859 --> 00:07:10.739
I'm a big user of both R and Python now, but I started out in R.

00:07:10.739 --> 00:07:15.220
And of course, Hadley and Garrett's book was huge at that time.

00:07:15.220 --> 00:07:18.339
You know, their early editions of that were out

00:07:18.339 --> 00:07:20.579
to get me started with the basics of using the language.

00:07:20.579 --> 00:07:26.739
And there was a little bit of online resource, but that only took me so far.

00:07:26.739 --> 00:07:30.019
It was really having my own data set and trying to do my own tasks

00:07:30.019 --> 00:07:33.059
with my own data that really kind of forced me to learn.

00:07:33.059 --> 00:07:35.859
And I learned almost entirely through trial and error.

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:42.179
And I think there's an element of that that we still need to have today.

00:07:42.179 --> 00:07:45.459
So I think that if programmers are not learning to program

00:07:45.459 --> 00:07:47.859
through trial and error, then they miss out on a lot of learning.

00:07:49.059 --> 00:07:52.100
In particular, one of the things that I see is people are using

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:54.420
Copilot to auto-complete their code lines.

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:58.579
And then their code lines don't work, and they don't know why they don't work.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:01.700
And so they have to go back and dig into it.

00:08:01.700 --> 00:08:03.459
And that process is very valuable, right?

00:08:03.459 --> 00:08:06.019
It's how you actually learn what's going on under the hood.

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:10.660
And then what I found is later on, after I'd gone through that initial kind of hump,

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:14.100
and I'd, you know, worked out how to get my code working,

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:18.820
I always say there's this period of success,

00:08:18.820 --> 00:08:22.260
where you kind of, you've passed the initial hump of success.

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:26.420
And that point is when you type a line of code and you expect it to work.

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:29.059
So there's a period you go through, you type a line of code and you say,

00:08:29.059 --> 00:08:34.500
I kind of know this is going to fail, because I don't understand it well enough yet.

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:35.940
But then there comes a point where you say,

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:40.419
I type a line of code and I'm surprised if it fails, right?

00:08:40.419 --> 00:08:46.179
When you hit that point, that's kind of your first step up point in learning to code, I think.

00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:49.460
And then once I passed that point and got further past it,

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.820
I then started to, you know, use a lot more advanced resources.

00:08:53.859 --> 00:08:58.340
A lot of, for example, Hadley's more advanced books on R.

00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:03.299
And started to really get under the hood of that language before I moved on to Python.

00:09:04.179 --> 00:09:06.419
So it was, it happened in various stages, right?

00:09:06.419 --> 00:09:10.419
But I think that the message I want to get across is the actual resources are not helpful

00:09:10.419 --> 00:09:14.419
if you're not actually applying them to your own context and data sets,

00:09:14.419 --> 00:09:16.099
because that's how you really learn, I think.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:22.500
I really like that answer, because it's the answer that I've given a lot of people.

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:26.419
And it makes me feel a little bit more justified, because I get asked a lot,

00:09:26.419 --> 00:09:27.859
should I learn this or should I learn that?

00:09:27.859 --> 00:09:29.460
Should I learn R or should I learn Python?

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:30.659
You use both, what do you think?

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:35.059
And my answer is always, you should go do both of them.

00:09:35.059 --> 00:09:40.419
You should go do whatever you find out there and try it,

00:09:40.419 --> 00:09:43.380
and physically type the things and do it.

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:47.940
And you will figure out from there what tools best suit your needs,

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:52.419
what brings you joy, what community you find around the stuff that you're doing.

00:09:53.059 --> 00:09:53.940
Go do the thing.

00:09:54.820 --> 00:09:59.299
And Keith, we're talking in the chat about how your book is actually the resource

00:09:59.299 --> 00:10:02.580
that a lot of people are now using to get into data science.

00:10:02.580 --> 00:10:04.500
So this is sort of a full circle moment.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:09.940
I'm going to put the link to his book, well, one of his books in the chat really quickly.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:15.140
And I figured that I would go ahead and just ask you to talk a little bit about your books.

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:17.460
I put the regression one in there, but you have another one.

00:10:18.020 --> 00:10:21.059
You want to give a quick pitch for both of those so we have some context?

00:10:22.099 --> 00:10:22.659
Yeah, sure.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:29.940
There's two areas I think that I learned very quickly were critical to the space

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:35.140
that I work in, which is the understanding of people and talent

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:41.299
and how they operate within organizations, but obviously have much broader applications.

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:47.219
So one area is regression, and the other area is organizational networks

00:10:47.219 --> 00:10:49.619
or network analysis and graph theory in general.

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:59.619
So regression is something that I think people have lost sight of a little.

00:10:59.619 --> 00:11:03.700
And one of the reasons why I wrote a book on regression was to try and get that back

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:08.340
into the forefront of people who are particularly interested in

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:10.179
doing data science to explain things.

00:11:11.539 --> 00:11:17.380
So we ended up getting into this situation, I think, in 2015 to 2018,

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:21.619
where a lot of the new kind of Python scikit-learn toolkit came on board.

00:11:21.619 --> 00:11:26.739
There was a huge amount of machine learning algorithms that weren't very explainable

00:11:27.299 --> 00:11:28.020
coming onto the...

00:11:29.140 --> 00:11:31.940
And Python and scikit-learn make them very easy to use.

00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:34.979
So we got into this situation where data scientists were jumping on

00:11:34.979 --> 00:11:39.380
and just running algorithms and getting results from them.

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:42.900
But a lot of people were having problems understanding those results,

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:46.260
and in particular, understanding that those results were predicting something,

00:11:46.260 --> 00:11:48.659
but they weren't necessarily explaining something.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:54.260
Now, in a lot of fields, like my field in econometrics and sociology

00:11:54.260 --> 00:11:55.780
and a whole bunch of other fields,

00:11:55.780 --> 00:11:58.580
the explanation of what's going on is more important than the prediction.

00:11:59.539 --> 00:12:05.059
And so regression is just an incredible Swiss army knife for doing that type of analysis,

00:12:05.059 --> 00:12:08.179
for being able to look inside a kind of phenomenon

00:12:08.179 --> 00:12:09.700
and understand what's actually going on.

00:12:09.700 --> 00:12:12.500
How do I explain how one thing leads to another?

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:15.539
And so one of the reasons I wrote the book was to get it back

00:12:15.539 --> 00:12:17.940
into the kind of consciousness of data scientists and say,

00:12:18.820 --> 00:12:21.299
there's a whole toolkit here, which you're kind of forgetting about,

00:12:22.179 --> 00:12:28.260
which has a lot of applicability in kind of explaining the problem you're dealing with.

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:34.820
So, and part of the book doesn't just cover the code and how to execute it.

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:37.539
A large proportion of the book covers like when you get the results,

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:39.219
what do you do with them?

00:12:39.219 --> 00:12:40.099
Like, what do they mean?

00:12:40.099 --> 00:12:41.780
How do you explain them to others?

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:44.260
How do you like make yourself a compelling data scientist

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:48.020
by being able to really well explain the outputs of your models, right?

00:12:49.059 --> 00:12:51.059
So that's kind of one of the books.

00:12:51.059 --> 00:12:53.059
And I'm actually working on a second edition of that,

00:12:53.059 --> 00:12:54.340
which is going to be fairly expanded.

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:55.940
So I've got a busy year ahead of me.

00:12:55.940 --> 00:12:56.659
Oh, that's awesome.

00:12:56.659 --> 00:12:57.619
On that one, yeah.

00:12:58.419 --> 00:12:59.700
The other one is kind of more niche,

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:01.940
which is around network analysis and graph theory.

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:04.020
So, you know, it's a huge area.

00:13:05.059 --> 00:13:07.299
I'm fascinated by the fact that data can be structured

00:13:07.299 --> 00:13:09.299
in ways that are different from rows and columns.

00:13:09.859 --> 00:13:12.099
So the idea behind a graph is that, you know,

00:13:12.739 --> 00:13:16.020
your kind of entities are stored in nodes

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:18.179
and your relationships between them are stored in edges.

00:13:19.219 --> 00:13:21.859
And it's just a beautiful data structure to work with.

00:13:21.859 --> 00:13:26.340
And it solves a lot of problems that like typical tidy tabular data does not solve.

00:13:27.380 --> 00:13:30.979
And so the role of that book is like to get people who are interested

00:13:30.979 --> 00:13:33.619
in those types of data structures and have applicability

00:13:33.619 --> 00:13:38.580
in their work or their studies like fluent in how to use them in R and Python.

00:13:40.099 --> 00:13:42.580
I even do a little bit of introduction to graph databases,

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:45.859
which is kind of the real burgeoning technology in this space now.

00:13:47.059 --> 00:13:51.059
So that was a joy to write that book, but it's a little bit more niche.

00:13:51.059 --> 00:13:54.500
I don't get the same readership on that book as I get on regression books.

00:13:55.460 --> 00:14:00.099
As someone who comes from operations research side of things

00:14:00.099 --> 00:14:03.380
and mathematical optimization, same.

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:08.900
I feel like whenever I talk about things like graphs and nodes and edges and stuff,

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:10.820
people's eyes sort of like glaze over.

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:14.659
But it's such a powerful tool to solve so many types of things.

00:14:15.219 --> 00:14:21.460
And you mentioned when I talked with you last that the results of those types of models

00:14:21.460 --> 00:14:25.780
can sometimes be a lot more intuitive to people to understand and explain,

00:14:26.340 --> 00:14:27.299
which I think is great.

00:14:27.940 --> 00:14:32.419
And as we're talking about psychometrics, we're talking about people data.

00:14:32.419 --> 00:14:36.020
I would love it if Arsenis could go ahead and unmute and ask his question

00:14:36.659 --> 00:14:37.940
because I thought it was interesting.

00:14:38.419 --> 00:14:38.900
Thank you.

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:39.940
Arsenis, are you available?

00:14:39.940 --> 00:14:40.900
There he is.

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:41.940
Hi, Libby.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:44.419
Hey, thank you so much for joining us, Keith.

00:14:44.419 --> 00:14:49.059
And I'm going to cheat a little bit because I'm going to double up here and ask

00:14:49.059 --> 00:14:52.179
my question that I put in Slido and one more about something you just asked.

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:59.700
So the question I put in Slido was, given your background with psychometrics and data science,

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:02.500
what do you think about the possibility of extracting

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:07.700
latent character traits about people from text?

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:11.460
The reason I'm asking that is this is something that I'm thinking about.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:17.619
There's a project that I'm thinking about that would be helpful for employers looking at

00:15:17.619 --> 00:15:20.179
individuals from recommendation letters, all that.

00:15:20.179 --> 00:15:28.340
So if I gave you 10 letters about me, is it possible to extract character traits

00:15:28.340 --> 00:15:29.940
rather than just my skills?

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:35.299
And if it's OK, I'm going to ask, do you have a title for the book on graph analysis?

00:15:35.299 --> 00:15:41.460
I'm presently getting into a project where I'm doing network analysis on skills.

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:43.299
I work for Indeed.

00:15:43.299 --> 00:15:45.619
And so this is kind of my domain.

00:15:45.619 --> 00:15:47.219
So, yeah, those two questions.

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:53.859
So I'll answer the second one first, which is basically any technical book I've written

00:15:53.859 --> 00:15:56.260
starts with handbook, the word handbook.

00:15:56.260 --> 00:15:58.020
So it's handbook of graphs and networks.

00:15:59.380 --> 00:16:02.340
And that's deliberate because I want the books to be very practical.

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:05.219
So I want you to be able to bring them up, open up the chapter and be able to get

00:16:05.219 --> 00:16:06.260
going with them.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:12.179
So the first question is a more kind of complex question, of course.

00:16:13.219 --> 00:16:19.700
I mean, in theory, the answer is yes, because text, the way that people express themselves

00:16:19.700 --> 00:16:23.619
and the way that they write words and the order in which they write those words and

00:16:23.619 --> 00:16:28.979
the types of words they use are indicative of their background and personality.

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:36.820
And but the problem is that you can't really identify that if you don't have an appropriate

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:40.020
model of personality that you're trying to map it against.

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:44.900
So you can't really say to a model, here's a bunch of text.

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:46.739
Tell me what this person is like, right?

00:16:47.539 --> 00:16:51.619
The model is unlikely to give you anything that's useful or structured from that.

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:58.099
But it is absolutely possible to say, here are a bunch of constructs of people's personalities.

00:16:58.099 --> 00:17:00.820
Here are the you know, how we're defining those constructs.

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:08.660
Can you kind of, you know, use can you use the language in this data source to map

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:11.140
individuals to these constructs?

00:17:12.979 --> 00:17:17.140
The I'm also very interested in the role of AI in this space.

00:17:17.140 --> 00:17:19.619
So I'm like not a massive AI convert, right?

00:17:19.619 --> 00:17:24.660
I approach AI very, very carefully because of kind of my not my under the hood knowledge

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:25.540
of how it operates.

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:27.859
But areas where I think.

00:17:28.979 --> 00:17:35.380
AI excels is where it can identify patterns that are kind of beyond the capacity of the

00:17:35.380 --> 00:17:36.900
human brain to identify, right?

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:40.819
Because the amount of data is just, you know, too large to handle.

00:17:40.819 --> 00:17:44.979
So, for example, we all a lot of us know situations where there's large company surveys

00:17:44.979 --> 00:17:49.060
where, like, tens of thousands of people have written text, and it's just not possible for

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:51.699
one person to read through those and synthesize them, right?

00:17:51.699 --> 00:17:55.140
So this is where kind of AI has a really big or large language models, in particular,

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:56.339
really big role to play.

00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:01.540
And I would, you know, there's things that we should consider.

00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:08.180
For example, one way of approaching your problem is to say, here's, you know, here's a bunch

00:18:08.180 --> 00:18:10.660
of letters that have been written by an individual.

00:18:11.619 --> 00:18:17.780
Now, I want you to use those letters to kind of extrapolate how this individual would respond

00:18:17.780 --> 00:18:18.979
to the following situation.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:22.819
And kind of see what that tells you, right?

00:18:22.819 --> 00:18:28.260
So I think AI gives us kind of more ways of looking at this problem than we have previously.

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:32.420
Previously, we would just have to rely on, like, breaking this text up into chunks and

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:37.219
using statistical models to relate it to, you know, to constructs that we're interested

00:18:37.219 --> 00:18:37.780
in.

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:42.900
Now we have, like, methods through which we can extrapolate to new situations and ask,

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:48.260
you know, models to determine, based on this input, how might somebody behave in this particular

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:50.900
situation or respond in this particular situation?

00:18:50.900 --> 00:18:54.500
So those are things I haven't done a lot of work in, but I think are definitely worth

00:18:54.500 --> 00:18:56.660
a lot of exploring with this new technology that we have.

00:18:58.180 --> 00:18:58.979
Amazing.

