00:19:48.180 --> 00:19:50.739
It was an anonymous question that was about,

00:19:50.739 --> 00:19:54.979
how do you balance self-learning with working time?

00:19:54.979 --> 00:19:57.380
And it says, I know you do a math problem every morning,

00:19:57.380 --> 00:20:00.020
but do you also plan structured study times?

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:02.500
Tell us a little bit about your math problem every morning.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:04.739
And I also see you do them on plane rides.

00:20:04.739 --> 00:20:05.699
I love it so much.

00:20:09.459 --> 00:20:12.420
The math problem every morning kind of started by accident.

00:20:14.099 --> 00:20:17.459
I started to do a little bit of math teaching about three years ago.

00:20:18.579 --> 00:20:23.060
And I just enjoyed the kind of cut and thrust of working with the student to kind of solve.

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:24.420
Some of these problems were very hard, right?

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:27.540
And I enjoyed the cut and thrust of working with the student to try and solve it.

00:20:27.540 --> 00:20:30.020
And I kind of enjoyed the euphoria of solving it.

00:20:30.020 --> 00:20:33.859
It kind of brought me back to what it was like when I was a student again myself.

00:20:34.819 --> 00:20:36.819
And then I thought, you know, if I did this every morning,

00:20:38.420 --> 00:20:40.339
what a confidence boost that would be, you know,

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:43.300
to like get started every morning having said,

00:20:43.300 --> 00:20:45.780
look, there's a hard problem, which I've already solved, you know.

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:48.739
And so I got into that habit.

00:20:48.739 --> 00:20:50.260
It doesn't work out every morning.

00:20:50.260 --> 00:20:54.180
You know, sometimes I have to go 10 mornings in a row before I finally solved the problem.

00:20:54.180 --> 00:21:00.180
But it is a really good kind of confidence boost and exercise for the brain, I think.

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:01.859
But a lot of people disagree with me and say,

00:21:01.859 --> 00:21:03.780
the first thing they need in the morning is a cup of coffee.

00:21:05.459 --> 00:21:06.660
Not a math problem?

00:21:06.660 --> 00:21:07.160
Shocker.

00:21:08.979 --> 00:21:13.540
But so that reminds me of the other part of your question.

00:21:13.540 --> 00:21:16.420
I got caught up in the math problem part.

00:21:16.979 --> 00:21:20.020
The other one is just how do you balance this sort of like

00:21:20.739 --> 00:21:23.619
intentional learning time with your work?

00:21:23.619 --> 00:21:24.119
Yeah.

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:26.979
I've got better and better at this, I think.

00:21:27.619 --> 00:21:33.619
Because first of all, like, if you're in work that really interests you,

00:21:34.180 --> 00:21:37.219
then work time is learning time, I think.

00:21:37.219 --> 00:21:40.819
Because you're doing problems and you're cracking things that

00:21:40.819 --> 00:21:44.180
require you to stretch your brain and do new stuff.

00:21:44.900 --> 00:21:49.380
And one of the things that I've always been kind of very conscientious about is,

00:21:50.339 --> 00:21:53.859
if as part of solving something in my day-to-day work,

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:57.219
I've come across something that's reproducible,

00:21:57.219 --> 00:22:02.099
you know, like, you know, it's a method or even a few lines of code where I thought,

00:22:02.099 --> 00:22:05.540
you know, I can see how I could use this for a lot of other things,

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:09.939
then I'm very deliberate about grasping that and making sure that I've recorded it.

00:22:09.939 --> 00:22:12.339
And, you know, it's kind of part of my toolkit.

00:22:13.459 --> 00:22:16.339
And if I think it's very generalizable in the sense that, like, I'm,

00:22:16.900 --> 00:22:19.699
by sharing it, I'm not sort of giving away any

00:22:19.699 --> 00:22:21.939
proprietary information or anything like that,

00:22:21.939 --> 00:22:24.180
then I'll also share it with the broader community and say,

00:22:24.180 --> 00:22:25.540
like, look at what I did today.

00:22:25.540 --> 00:22:26.579
I think this is super useful.

00:22:26.579 --> 00:22:29.060
Maybe you guys would find this useful too.

00:22:30.660 --> 00:22:32.420
So that's something I've always deliberately done.

00:22:33.380 --> 00:22:36.739
In the last maybe two or three years, my job became extremely busy.

00:22:36.739 --> 00:22:39.699
So it became harder and harder to actually do real technical work.

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:43.780
Because one of the things you get in more senior positions is you get dragged into

00:22:44.339 --> 00:22:49.219
a lot of meetings and a lot of things that, like, take you away from hands-on keyboard work.

00:22:50.020 --> 00:22:54.099
And during that period, one of the things I deliberately did is kind of I

00:22:55.140 --> 00:23:00.099
tried my best that it wasn't always successful to kind of designate my Fridays as coding day.

00:23:01.300 --> 00:23:05.540
And I would make, like, a lot of people feel bad about interrupting my coding day.

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:09.619
And so that created an environment where I did get a lot of time on Fridays

00:23:09.619 --> 00:23:10.739
to actually do technical work.

00:23:10.739 --> 00:23:13.619
And I would, like, hold it off until Friday if I wanted to do it.

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:18.180
So if there's any of you kind of on the call who are kind of struggling with that balance,

00:23:18.180 --> 00:23:23.140
because I know it's a really common problem, you know, like, where do you find time to do

00:23:23.140 --> 00:23:27.699
technical work versus have to sit in meetings and, you know, where you can't get hands-on keyboard?

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:32.500
One tip is, like, designate a block of time for it.

00:23:32.500 --> 00:23:35.300
And another tip is, like, don't be afraid to make your colleagues feel

00:23:35.300 --> 00:23:36.819
guilty about interrupting that time.

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:38.739
Yeah.

00:23:38.739 --> 00:23:44.180
Actually, Rachel just mentioned in the chat that she and I are both trying no meetings Wednesdays.

00:23:44.180 --> 00:23:45.300
So that was yesterday for me.

00:23:45.300 --> 00:23:47.219
And it was the first time I'd actually achieved it.

00:23:47.219 --> 00:23:54.020
It was the first week since I started trying it that I actually got declined all the meetings,

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:55.140
moved everything around.

00:23:56.260 --> 00:23:58.020
And I got so much coding done.

00:23:58.020 --> 00:23:59.380
I did so many productive things.

00:23:59.380 --> 00:24:01.540
I caught up on so many admin tasks.

00:24:01.540 --> 00:24:02.660
Highly recommend.

00:24:02.660 --> 00:24:03.699
It's not always easy.

00:24:03.699 --> 00:24:08.979
But also, I will say, I took a pre-calculus course a couple of years ago through, I think,

00:24:08.979 --> 00:24:13.859
Arizona State University on edX or something, because it's free.

00:24:13.859 --> 00:24:15.060
Gosh, go do that.

00:24:15.060 --> 00:24:16.739
It was so much fun.

00:24:16.739 --> 00:24:19.459
I enjoyed that pre-cal class so much.

00:24:20.660 --> 00:24:23.699
I highly recommend, like, getting some math in your day.

00:24:23.699 --> 00:24:28.500
That high that you mentioned of, like, solving a problem is so good.

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:30.900
It's also it's kind of like squashing a bug in your code.

00:24:32.339 --> 00:24:32.900
Okay.

