00:24:56.739 --> 00:24:58.099
Nicole had a question.

00:24:58.099 --> 00:24:59.060
Nicole, will you be?

00:24:59.699 --> 00:25:01.859
Nicole Burke, if you're available.

00:25:01.859 --> 00:25:02.979
You want to unmute and ask.

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:05.060
Hi, Keith.

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:06.579
It's really nice to meet you.

00:25:06.579 --> 00:25:09.219
So I am a big fan of your network work.

00:25:09.219 --> 00:25:13.780
I am a psych PhD who also did a lot of network, like, analysis in my doctoral work.

00:25:13.780 --> 00:25:17.060
So, yeah, I just kind of wanted to ask you, like, what kind of questions are you, like,

00:25:17.060 --> 00:25:20.660
most excited about, like, using networks to kind of, like, ask in the people analytics space?

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:23.380
And do you kind of see, like, networks still, like, taking off?

00:25:23.380 --> 00:25:27.300
Like, I know in that space, I know it's kind of, like, slow adopting or slow moving.

00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:29.780
So, yeah, I would just love to kind of hear your thoughts about that.

00:25:30.739 --> 00:25:31.939
Yeah, thanks, Nicole.

00:25:31.939 --> 00:25:36.020
And whenever I hear that somebody's actually using stuff that I put together, it always

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:36.979
makes me really happy.

00:25:36.979 --> 00:25:39.540
And so thanks for telling me that.

00:25:40.339 --> 00:25:53.060
The, I guess, in terms of whether people are using network analysis and that type of approach

00:25:53.060 --> 00:25:57.939
really depends on what I found is it really, really depends on the data that they have

00:25:57.939 --> 00:25:58.660
available to them.

00:25:58.660 --> 00:26:02.979
So, one of the big blockers to people using a network based approach to their analytics

00:26:02.979 --> 00:26:07.140
is the fact that they don't have data in any sort of form that you can put in a graph.

00:26:08.180 --> 00:26:13.380
And I actually dedicate a whole chapter in my book to, like, how do you transform rectangular

00:26:13.380 --> 00:26:17.939
data into graph data for the purposes of solving a problem?

00:26:17.939 --> 00:26:20.099
Because that's the biggest blocker that I've seen.

00:26:20.099 --> 00:26:24.099
You know, like, if you go into a random organization, you show them a graph, a way of working

00:26:24.099 --> 00:26:25.780
with things in graph, they'll say, that's great.

00:26:25.780 --> 00:26:27.859
But none of my data looks like that.

00:26:28.660 --> 00:26:34.739
But that said, if you can get your data in that form, there's immense number of really

00:26:34.739 --> 00:26:36.739
impactful problems you can solve with them.

00:26:37.859 --> 00:26:41.140
And some of them are even problems that you wouldn't think that you would be able to solve

00:26:41.140 --> 00:26:42.099
with graphs, right?

00:26:42.099 --> 00:26:48.900
So, a couple of examples, a couple of, you know, a few years ago, I was faced with this

00:26:48.900 --> 00:26:54.339
problem of, like, a really open problem of, you know, if we, if we were to reorganize

00:26:54.579 --> 00:27:02.180
our organization with different organizational units, you know, than the ones we have today,

00:27:02.979 --> 00:27:07.219
what kind of organizational units would be most optimal to ensure that people collaborate

00:27:07.219 --> 00:27:08.180
with each other better?

00:27:09.859 --> 00:27:15.380
And I basically created a massive graph full of a bunch of employees, got data on, like,

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:21.939
their current collaboration, you know, populated the edges with that, used various community

00:27:21.939 --> 00:27:26.099
detection algorithms to try and identify, like, where are the hotspots of collaboration?

00:27:26.099 --> 00:27:30.099
And very quickly, it was obvious that there was one way of organizing that was particularly,

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:34.979
you know, conducive to high levels of collaboration.

00:27:34.979 --> 00:27:38.979
And to be able to put an analytic point of view behind that is, like, a really powerful,

00:27:38.979 --> 00:27:43.300
you know, because most people view organizational, you know, network analysis and organizational

00:27:43.300 --> 00:27:48.260
behavior as a very, like, touchy-feely thing that that's not very data driven.

00:27:48.260 --> 00:27:52.099
So, to be able to actually drive a data-based approach to that is huge.

00:27:52.099 --> 00:27:56.420
And to be able to put good visualizations behind it, and this is along the lines of

00:27:56.420 --> 00:27:59.780
what Libby was saying earlier around making things intuitive.

00:27:59.780 --> 00:28:04.660
You know, if you can visualize a bunch of dots with those dots coming together more

00:28:04.660 --> 00:28:08.660
in a particular framework than in others, you're actually, people can actually see the

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:11.619
dynamics of what's going on in front of their eyes.

00:28:11.619 --> 00:28:14.900
And that can be hugely impactful to them, you know, believing what you're putting in

00:28:14.900 --> 00:28:15.459
front of them.

00:28:16.020 --> 00:28:21.859
So, and more recently, you know, we've been using graphs to solve questions of time and

00:28:21.859 --> 00:28:26.500
how people are using their time to be able to make inferences of what people are doing

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:27.140
with their time.

00:28:28.819 --> 00:28:32.819
You know, and even then, you don't have direct data on that, but the inferences you can make

00:28:32.819 --> 00:28:36.979
from the connections in your graph can make you, like, very, very certain that, like,

00:28:36.979 --> 00:28:41.540
a certain type of activity is being done by people at a certain point in time.

00:28:41.540 --> 00:28:46.979
And that helps you kind of analyze, you know, a lot of things about, you know, efficiency,

00:28:46.979 --> 00:28:49.859
workforce efficiency, and a bunch of other topics.

00:28:49.859 --> 00:28:52.260
And so all of these things are very possible.

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:55.540
But one of the things I will say is we've done a lot of work on engineering our data

00:28:55.540 --> 00:28:57.780
well to be able to go into graphs.

00:28:57.780 --> 00:29:02.020
Without that, it's much harder to kind of get started on that topic, I think.

