00:29:28.819 --> 00:29:35.459
I think I had written, yes, as a self-taught data analytics person and computer programmer.

00:29:35.459 --> 00:29:42.180
What would you say is the most important AI-related skill to learn for the future and

00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:43.699
to stay ahead in the workplace?

00:29:43.699 --> 00:29:49.939
I know you've written about, you know, things such as AI agents, but what do you see as

00:29:49.939 --> 00:29:55.619
more important, like, whether it's, like, for me to learn if I wanted to get a good

00:29:55.619 --> 00:30:01.619
job or really impact the business, whether it would be specifically knowing the techniques

00:30:01.619 --> 00:30:07.699
or helping organizations know how to implement AI, something like that?

00:30:09.459 --> 00:30:10.180
Yeah, thanks.

00:30:10.180 --> 00:30:11.619
That's a really, really good question.

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:18.900
And first thing I would say is, like, AI is moving so quickly and at such an early stage

00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:22.979
that anything I say now could be very dated in a year or two, right?

00:30:22.979 --> 00:30:25.859
And I think that's important to call out.

00:30:25.859 --> 00:30:29.459
But I think there's a balance here, right?

00:30:29.540 --> 00:30:34.180
One part is, like, learning the technology behind AI, right?

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:37.859
So there's a lot of very rapidly moving technology.

00:30:37.859 --> 00:30:44.099
As these models develop, you've got, like, things like tool calling.

00:30:44.099 --> 00:30:46.900
You've got to learn things like data validation.

00:30:46.900 --> 00:30:53.619
There's a whole set of tooling that's involved in building an AI agent, for example, that

00:30:53.619 --> 00:30:56.420
you could think about skilling yourself up with, right?

00:30:56.979 --> 00:31:02.900
But on the other hand, there's the whole issue of the trustworthiness of AI and the likelihood

00:31:02.900 --> 00:31:07.939
that the response you get from a large language model is usable without a lot of risk to your

00:31:07.939 --> 00:31:10.900
organization or to the work that you're doing.

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:16.579
And that's much less of a technical, at least it's much less of a coding problem and much

00:31:16.579 --> 00:31:21.859
more of a kind of how knowledgeable are you about how these models work and what the benefits

00:31:21.859 --> 00:31:23.939
and risks of using them are.

00:31:24.500 --> 00:31:33.140
I would probably say that if you are not in a situation where you have to actively build

00:31:33.140 --> 00:31:39.300
AI workflows or AI technology right now, I would limit the amount of time that you're

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:42.900
spending learning how to, like, code agents and things like that.

00:31:42.900 --> 00:31:47.300
Because if you're not doing it right now, you don't really have a use case to use it

00:31:47.300 --> 00:31:47.300


00:31:47.300 --> 00:31:52.739
And by the time you do have a use case, it could have changed a lot between, you know,

00:31:53.459 --> 00:31:55.140
between now and then.

00:31:55.140 --> 00:31:59.619
So for that side of the things, I would be saying, you know, stay in touch with the latest

00:31:59.619 --> 00:32:05.060
developments, but you don't necessarily have to have fluent hands-on keyboard skills for

00:32:05.060 --> 00:32:09.619
that unless you're directly working on something where you're building something related to

00:32:09.619 --> 00:32:10.099
it, right?

00:32:11.619 --> 00:32:15.780
On the other side of things, I think these issues of how trustworthy are the results

00:32:15.780 --> 00:32:20.739
of large language models, when they're safe, when they're not safe, those issues will persist

00:32:21.459 --> 00:32:24.180
and they'll persist for a long time, possibly forever.

00:32:26.020 --> 00:32:29.939
And so being knowledgeable about that and being able to, like, advise appropriately

00:32:29.939 --> 00:32:33.780
and, you know, to be able to deal with super AI enthusiasts, to be able to, like, pull

00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:37.219
them back and say, hold on, there's a few things you need to think about here before

00:32:37.219 --> 00:32:39.380
you go gung-ho on this.

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:43.219
That skill is very useful in all contexts, I think.

00:32:43.219 --> 00:32:45.300
So that's one I would index on heavily.

00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:47.540
It's like, stay in touch with what the experts are saying.

00:32:48.099 --> 00:32:51.939
Look for a set of people that you trust in terms of what they're saying about this, because

00:32:51.939 --> 00:32:55.780
there's a lot of hype out there, which you have to be very careful of.

00:32:56.900 --> 00:33:00.339
Try to find a few people you can trust, follow those people, read about it, make sure you're

00:33:00.339 --> 00:33:03.459
staying up to date on what we're discovering about these models.

00:33:04.660 --> 00:33:10.260
And that is, like, something I would work on, you know, now and make sure you're staying

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:14.339
fluent in it, whereas the technical and coding aspects of it, that depends on your situation

00:33:14.339 --> 00:33:15.699
and whether you need it right now or not.

00:33:17.540 --> 00:33:18.339
Awesome.

00:33:18.339 --> 00:33:18.979
Great advice.

00:33:18.979 --> 00:33:20.500
Great question, Ashley.

00:33:20.500 --> 00:33:21.380
Thank you for asking.

00:33:22.180 --> 00:33:27.300
And I will chime in and say, with the AI stuff, just question everything.

00:33:28.339 --> 00:33:30.180
It's, like, the biggest advice I can give you.

00:33:30.180 --> 00:33:34.739
I wrote something a couple days ago, and I decided to hand it to Claude and be like,

00:33:34.739 --> 00:33:36.260
Claude, what do you think of this script?

00:33:36.979 --> 00:33:39.699
A script that I had gotten, ChatGPT's help writing.

00:33:39.699 --> 00:33:40.979
I didn't write all of it myself.

00:33:40.979 --> 00:33:42.339
I got kind of assistance.

00:33:42.339 --> 00:33:42.979
Gave it to Claude.

00:33:43.619 --> 00:33:45.540
I said, is this going to do what I think it's going to do?

00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:48.660
And Claude said, no, it's not going to work for all these reasons.

00:33:48.660 --> 00:33:52.979
And it listed, like, eight big reasons that were, like, these are never going to work.

00:33:52.979 --> 00:33:54.739
And I'm, like, I think Claude's wrong.

00:33:54.739 --> 00:33:55.540
I think all these are wrong.

00:33:56.099 --> 00:33:57.540
Ran my code, tested it.

00:33:57.540 --> 00:33:58.420
Claude was wrong.

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:00.500
I came back to Claude and went, you're wrong.

00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:02.900
You have to make a point.

00:34:02.900 --> 00:34:04.339
My code's totally fine.

00:34:04.339 --> 00:34:05.619
And it's, like, oh, I'm sorry.

00:34:05.619 --> 00:34:06.020
You're right.

00:34:06.020 --> 00:34:06.660
It is fine.

00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:09.300
Here's all the reason why it's great and it's going to work.

00:34:09.300 --> 00:34:11.300
I'm, like, okay.

00:34:11.300 --> 00:34:12.419
So question everything.

00:34:12.979 --> 00:34:13.379
All right.

00:34:13.379 --> 00:34:14.899
Thank you so much for that question.

00:34:14.899 --> 00:34:18.340
Let's go find another fantastic question.

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:24.500
I feel like we had another one that I really liked that was anonymous.

00:34:24.500 --> 00:34:25.699
And it was about math.

00:34:25.699 --> 00:34:26.419
There we go.

00:34:26.419 --> 00:34:32.340
I did an anonymous question that says, interested in topological data analysis, but intimidated.

00:34:32.340 --> 00:34:36.580
Are there any resources or packages you would recommend exploring?

00:34:36.580 --> 00:34:40.500
I am not sure if you're in the topology mathematical space, Keith.

00:34:41.459 --> 00:34:42.659
Oh, that one.

00:34:42.659 --> 00:34:46.419
So, I mean, I did study topology when I studied mathematics.

00:34:46.419 --> 00:34:54.659
But as it applies to data science, not hugely knowledgeable on that topic.

00:34:55.459 --> 00:35:00.820
I do hear topology used a lot in terms of networks.

00:35:00.820 --> 00:35:05.699
And I think that that tends to be a description of, like, how your network is designed and,

00:35:05.780 --> 00:35:11.060
like, what are the determinants of what defines a node and how you're connecting your nodes.

00:35:11.939 --> 00:35:18.100
Topology in general has a kind of a meaning of, like, how are you shaping things in the

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:19.139
way that you're working.

00:35:19.939 --> 00:35:23.860
But outside of that, those general comments, I wouldn't want to pretend I'm an expert on that

00:35:23.860 --> 00:35:24.739
topic by any means.

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:26.100
Well, I don't either.

00:35:26.100 --> 00:35:29.699
If there's anybody else in the chat who happens to know a little bit more about topological

00:35:29.699 --> 00:35:32.659
analysis, leave some resources.

00:35:32.739 --> 00:35:37.139
For whoever asked that wonderful anonymous question, thank you, anonymous asker.

00:35:38.419 --> 00:35:39.620
We have one here.

00:35:40.340 --> 00:35:40.820
Let's see.

00:35:46.020 --> 00:35:48.179
This one says, Libby, can you please read this?

00:35:48.179 --> 00:35:48.899
So, I will.

00:35:51.860 --> 00:35:53.139
It's from Trey Hendricks.

00:35:53.139 --> 00:36:00.020
And it says, I'm interested in how talent is measured among white collar workers, since

00:36:00.020 --> 00:36:02.179
it seems challenging to operationalize.

00:36:02.179 --> 00:36:04.179
It does sound challenging to operationalize.

00:36:04.179 --> 00:36:09.780
Could you share some of the metrics you use and how you address the limitations of more

00:36:09.780 --> 00:36:12.419
straightforward measures like time in the office?

00:36:15.219 --> 00:36:16.020
Yeah, thanks.

00:36:17.219 --> 00:36:18.659
It's a really interesting question.

00:36:19.459 --> 00:36:24.419
And it obviously takes the time up of a huge number of what we would probably call

00:36:24.419 --> 00:36:32.020
psychometricians nowadays, whose kind of job it is to determine ways of measuring constructs

00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:33.620
related to success in the workplace.

00:36:33.620 --> 00:36:41.459
And certainly for topics like time in the office, that comes down to almost entirely

00:36:41.459 --> 00:36:43.939
like what data you have available to you, right?

00:36:43.939 --> 00:36:48.580
It's quite possible that in a lot of organizations, there's just no way of measuring that if there's

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:50.739
no systems in place to be able to capture it.

00:36:50.739 --> 00:36:54.659
Whereas in other organizations, you might have like badge in, badge out systems.

00:36:54.659 --> 00:36:58.979
And that might give you fairly accurate views of people's time in the office.

00:36:58.979 --> 00:37:03.060
But you're also dealing with questions of privacy about whether you should even be using

00:37:03.060 --> 00:37:04.979
that data or not.

00:37:04.979 --> 00:37:09.219
And so there's a lot of complexities around that question.

00:37:09.219 --> 00:37:15.300
I would break it into kind of two components, which is there are a set of constructs which

00:37:15.939 --> 00:37:23.939
we kind of organizations impose on that relate to what they regard as success of their employees.

00:37:23.939 --> 00:37:28.659
And I'm specifically referring to white collar employees with this.

00:37:29.620 --> 00:37:34.179
And those are usually designed by like psychometricians and talent teams, and they'll often be part

00:37:34.179 --> 00:37:39.860
of development structures or evaluation forms, all of those things.

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:45.060
And those things tend to be developed on a theoretical basis using research.

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:48.820
It's usually qualitative research with your employee base.

00:37:49.620 --> 00:37:53.620
But then you have this question, which is more interesting for me as a kind of quantitative

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:58.179
individual, which is what data can you get to kind of validate those constructs?

00:37:58.739 --> 00:37:59.379
Right.

00:37:59.379 --> 00:38:08.260
So one of your constructs might be that you're successful in a particular job over a particular

00:38:08.260 --> 00:38:09.379
time period.

00:38:09.379 --> 00:38:14.820
And there's several constructs, several measures which you could use to validate that construct

00:38:14.820 --> 00:38:15.699
for individuals.

00:38:16.419 --> 00:38:18.899
One is what's their performance rating?

00:38:18.899 --> 00:38:23.860
But what if your performance rating system is rubbish and everyone gets the middle performance

00:38:23.860 --> 00:38:28.260
rating and nobody gets anything else, which is quite common in many environments?

00:38:29.219 --> 00:38:30.899
You also have promotion, right?

00:38:30.899 --> 00:38:34.340
But what if you're in an environment where promotion is automatic after a certain period

00:38:34.340 --> 00:38:34.899
of time?

00:38:34.899 --> 00:38:37.780
Then that's not a great differentiator of success.

00:38:37.780 --> 00:38:44.179
So a lot of what my work involves is how do we take data that could be indicators of a

00:38:44.179 --> 00:38:48.580
certain construct and use it in some sort of intelligent way to try and answer some

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:49.459
of the questions.

00:38:49.459 --> 00:38:53.060
And often there's a lot of data that we'll throw out because it's just not useful from

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:54.500
an analytic perspective.

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:57.060
And there's other data that turns out to be very related.

00:38:57.060 --> 00:39:03.379
And one of the things, going back to network analysis, to be able to understand like colleagues

00:39:03.379 --> 00:39:08.820
networks and how they interact with other people, that turns out in many, many use cases

00:39:08.820 --> 00:39:13.459
to be a very, very valuable indicator of a lot of things with white collar workers, right?

00:39:13.459 --> 00:39:18.899
If they have large networks or if they're very central to their networks, those sorts

00:39:18.899 --> 00:39:21.219
of indicators I found are often very valuable.

00:39:21.860 --> 00:39:22.899
But it's a hard question.

00:39:22.899 --> 00:39:24.020
It depends on the context.

00:39:24.020 --> 00:39:25.699
There's a lot of subjectivity to it.

00:39:26.659 --> 00:39:32.260
But the job of like a quantitative individual like me is to try and match those constructs

00:39:32.260 --> 00:39:33.780
to some sort of data indicators.

00:39:35.060 --> 00:39:35.379
Yeah.

00:39:35.379 --> 00:39:40.580
And to use your subject matter expertise and all of your education and stuff to sort of

00:39:40.580 --> 00:39:43.939
bring that nuance to the forefront and say, this isn't an easy answer.

00:39:43.939 --> 00:39:44.979
This is a tough answer.

00:39:44.979 --> 00:39:46.659
We have imperfect measures, all of that stuff.

00:39:47.620 --> 00:39:49.379
Thank you so much for the question, Trey.

00:39:49.379 --> 00:39:52.739
And Cecilia had a question that really ties on to this one.

00:39:52.739 --> 00:39:59.139
Speaking of the sort of subject matter expertise, Cecilia, would you like to hop in here and

00:39:59.139 --> 00:39:59.300
ask?

00:40:00.179 --> 00:40:00.739
Yes.

00:40:00.739 --> 00:40:00.979
Hi.

00:40:01.620 --> 00:40:08.899
So my question comes from the fact that I talked to you on LinkedIn and I saw the path that

00:40:08.899 --> 00:40:15.060
you had and I found it very intriguing because from a PhD in math and then the first role

00:40:15.060 --> 00:40:22.179
you had in industry was an engagement manager role and then into technical, more technical

00:40:22.179 --> 00:40:22.899
data science.

00:40:22.899 --> 00:40:29.620
So I was wondering if that role, that engagement role, helped you bridge this switch from academia

00:40:29.620 --> 00:40:30.340
to industry?

00:40:30.899 --> 00:40:36.739
Or like how did that role help you maybe like choose the skill you wanted to build?

00:40:37.459 --> 00:40:37.939
Thank you.

00:40:39.060 --> 00:40:39.620
Yeah.

00:40:39.620 --> 00:40:40.340
Thank you, Cecilia.

00:40:40.340 --> 00:40:42.419
I don't get to talk about this part of my career very much.

00:40:42.419 --> 00:40:44.500
So it's great that you brought it up.

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:48.979
It was a real baptism of fire to move from academia into industry.

00:40:48.979 --> 00:40:49.219
Right.

00:40:49.219 --> 00:40:54.020
And I think anybody who's done it probably kind of can relate to this, particularly as

00:40:54.020 --> 00:40:56.179
a mathematician and a pure mathematician at that.

00:40:56.179 --> 00:41:00.580
You know, the way I describe it is it's a very enclosed and protected environment.

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:07.300
And because of the kind of intellectual kind of nature of that environment, there's very

00:41:07.300 --> 00:41:11.379
little investment in how you communicate as an individual.

00:41:11.379 --> 00:41:15.219
So a lot of the attitude is, you know, if you don't understand what I'm saying, that's

00:41:15.219 --> 00:41:17.060
because you're not as smart as I am.

00:41:17.060 --> 00:41:17.699
Right.

00:41:17.699 --> 00:41:23.300
And that's kind of a protective envelope that a lot of like, particularly in mathematics,

00:41:23.300 --> 00:41:27.219
there's some that kind of prevents you from having to work hard at how you communicate

00:41:27.219 --> 00:41:29.300
because you've got that sort of comfort blanket.

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:35.139
But when you move into industry, it's like, you know, sometimes more than half of getting

00:41:35.139 --> 00:41:40.179
to the right outcome is how you communicate your approach and how you solve your problem.

00:41:40.179 --> 00:41:44.580
Because if you can't, if people are not bought into the solution, they won't go along with

00:41:44.580 --> 00:41:44.659
it.

00:41:44.659 --> 00:41:45.939
And all that work is wasted.

00:41:45.939 --> 00:41:46.100
Right.

00:41:46.100 --> 00:41:47.459
They have to believe what you're saying.

00:41:48.340 --> 00:41:52.419
And that was just I had to learn that skill because that was not something that was in

00:41:52.419 --> 00:41:54.820
any way taught to me in my academic career.

00:41:54.820 --> 00:41:58.100
And that took maybe a year or two to really build my confidence there.

00:41:58.820 --> 00:42:02.020
And it was incredibly enriching because I don't think I'd be the person I am today if

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:03.219
I hadn't have gone through that.

00:42:03.219 --> 00:42:06.739
You know, certainly I wouldn't be a good communicator by any means.

00:42:08.260 --> 00:42:12.500
And and I think that's I've taken that through with me because it's taught me the value of

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:13.219
communication.

00:42:13.780 --> 00:42:14.020
Right.

00:42:14.020 --> 00:42:19.459
I think if there's a danger that if I'd gone straight from academia into into data science,

00:42:19.459 --> 00:42:22.179
I might have still had that mindset of, look, you don't understand my code.

00:42:22.179 --> 00:42:23.620
That's because you're not as smart as I am.

00:42:24.899 --> 00:42:29.860
But I know now that writing the code is one thing, explaining the outcome of the code

00:42:29.860 --> 00:42:33.459
and being able to convince people that you know what you're doing and that they can trust

00:42:33.459 --> 00:42:37.300
you because you have good, good knowledge and a good foundation to be able to listen

00:42:37.300 --> 00:42:41.060
to their questions and understand what it is that's concerning them, to be able to give

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:43.540
you give tailored responses to that.

00:42:43.540 --> 00:42:47.300
All of those things I learned in those first three years of my career, I think, which have

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:48.899
served me well in the long run.

00:42:50.419 --> 00:42:54.100
But the bottom line is I love the technical work.

00:42:54.100 --> 00:42:54.340
Right.

00:42:54.340 --> 00:42:58.739
And I was always going to come back to something where I was really deeply using my brain to

00:42:58.739 --> 00:43:01.379
kind of solve interesting technical problems.

00:43:01.379 --> 00:43:04.899
I just have that additional toolkit now, I think, because of those early years of my

00:43:04.899 --> 00:43:05.219
career.

00:43:07.379 --> 00:43:09.699
Thank you for the fantastic questions, Cecilia.

00:43:09.699 --> 00:43:10.820
Everybody really liked that one.

00:43:10.820 --> 00:43:11.459
And thanks.

00:43:11.459 --> 00:43:12.100
Thanks, Keith.

00:43:13.459 --> 00:43:15.060
I had a question.

00:43:15.060 --> 00:43:16.659
Let's see if I can find it again.

00:43:18.739 --> 00:43:20.820
That is a good follow up to this one.

00:43:22.899 --> 00:43:24.340
It was Siraj.

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:29.219
If you happen to be able to unmute and ask your question, I would love that.

00:43:29.219 --> 00:43:30.580
We only have about 10 minutes left.

00:43:30.580 --> 00:43:32.979
Let's see if we can fit into just a couple more questions for Keith.

00:43:34.899 --> 00:43:35.620
Sorry, Libby.

00:43:35.620 --> 00:43:38.020
I didn't find Siraj fast enough.

00:43:38.020 --> 00:43:38.659
I was just checking.

00:43:38.659 --> 00:43:39.540
Oh, that's OK.

00:43:41.620 --> 00:43:44.179
I think I found Siraj.

00:43:44.179 --> 00:43:44.580
Thank you.

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:46.659
Hey, guys.

00:43:46.659 --> 00:43:48.580
Sorry, my mic is on mute.

00:43:49.699 --> 00:43:50.340
Thanks, Libby.

00:43:50.340 --> 00:43:51.139
I'll make it quick.

00:43:51.939 --> 00:43:54.179
I just wanted to get your perspective, Dr.

00:43:54.179 --> 00:44:00.500
Keith, on imposter syndrome, especially for people who are making some sort of transition

00:44:00.500 --> 00:44:02.100
in their career into data science.

00:44:02.100 --> 00:44:04.820
I myself used to work in marketing before.

00:44:05.379 --> 00:44:10.419
And I'm kind of making a career change into data science, although I did some work in

00:44:10.419 --> 00:44:12.820
data analysis and a little bit of modeling before.

00:44:12.820 --> 00:44:15.300
So it's a question that a lot of people have.

00:44:15.300 --> 00:44:20.020
And I just wanted to get your perspective, since you also made a transition of sorts

00:44:20.020 --> 00:44:26.179
and also maybe you've managed teams where people have started off as a new data scientist

00:44:26.179 --> 00:44:27.219
in the field.

00:44:27.219 --> 00:44:28.739
So yeah, just happy to hear your thoughts.

00:44:30.179 --> 00:44:31.219
Yeah, thanks, Siraj.

00:44:32.659 --> 00:44:37.379
I mean, imposter syndrome is a really big thing in many, many fields, right?

00:44:38.179 --> 00:44:43.540
Anytime you kind of change your environment and you often have to join a bunch of people

00:44:43.540 --> 00:44:49.540
who you perceive to have substantially greater knowledge than you in the field is a massive

00:44:49.620 --> 00:44:51.860
opportunity for you to feel kind of imposter syndrome.

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:54.100
And it's perfectly normal, I think, to feel it.

00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:56.260
And I felt it myself on many, many occasions.

00:44:58.659 --> 00:45:05.379
I honestly believe that you overcome imposter syndrome through, first of all, you have to

00:45:05.379 --> 00:45:07.459
be in the right field, right?

00:45:07.459 --> 00:45:12.100
If you are not feeling comfortable in the field you're working in, if you don't have

00:45:12.100 --> 00:45:16.979
that passion for it, if you're not interested in it, it's likely that that imposter syndrome

00:45:16.979 --> 00:45:20.500
will continue because the incentive is not there for you to become more knowledgeable

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:24.179
and to become more fluent at it because you don't enjoy it, right?

00:45:24.979 --> 00:45:26.340
So that's the first thing I would say.

00:45:27.540 --> 00:45:33.060
If you are lucky enough to be working in a field that you love, you get over your imposter

00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:37.060
syndrome through good hard work and collaboration with your colleagues and learning, right?

00:45:37.060 --> 00:45:41.459
Where you go through enough experiences that you get that pattern recognition so that you

00:45:41.459 --> 00:45:43.300
can say, you know, I've seen this before.

00:45:43.300 --> 00:45:44.100
I know what to do.

00:45:44.820 --> 00:45:48.419
And over time, you start to have success from that.

00:45:48.419 --> 00:45:51.620
And that's the confidence building, which helps you get over imposter syndrome.

00:45:51.620 --> 00:45:56.899
So I mentioned previously, like, this period when I was learning to code and where, like,

00:45:56.899 --> 00:45:59.060
I got to a point where I realized, hold on.

00:45:59.060 --> 00:46:01.620
Now, when I'm typing my lines of code, I actually expect them to work.

00:46:02.419 --> 00:46:04.580
That's, like, a huge step up for me.

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:07.300
That was, like, step one of me overcoming my imposter syndrome, right?

00:46:07.300 --> 00:46:10.820
Because then I could get on calls with my colleague and I could, like, live code and

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:13.300
not be worried about embarrassing myself, right?

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:16.419
So there's various ways in which you can overcome it.

00:46:16.419 --> 00:46:19.300
But the first thing I would say is you're probably not going to overcome it if you're

00:46:19.300 --> 00:46:20.899
not working in a field that you enjoy.

00:46:22.260 --> 00:46:25.300
If you are working in a field you enjoy, it's hard work and learning.

00:46:25.300 --> 00:46:29.060
And, you know, putting yourself out there and making the mistakes that help you learn

00:46:29.060 --> 00:46:31.060
is what helps you overcome imposter syndrome, I think.

00:46:32.739 --> 00:46:34.419
I just said the same thing in the chat.

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:38.979
The evidence is what leads to confidence, but you can't get the evidence part until

00:46:38.979 --> 00:46:42.659
you actually do the stuff, which requires failing a lot.

00:46:42.659 --> 00:46:44.500
