00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:42.340
But, you know, I am – I have a little bit of a concern about, like, what data science

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:46.739
is becoming in the kind of world of large language models, right?

00:51:46.739 --> 00:51:51.219
And I see a lot of people who are data scientists, but what they're actually doing is they're

00:51:51.219 --> 00:51:54.659
just – they're really doing software engineering, right?

00:51:54.659 --> 00:51:58.419
They're interacting with language models and trying to get them to do stuff for them.

00:51:58.419 --> 00:52:01.060
But if you look at the code that they're writing, it's software code.

00:52:01.060 --> 00:52:02.419
It's not data science code.

00:52:02.979 --> 00:52:08.419
For me, like, data science is working with data, understanding the patterns in that data,

00:52:08.979 --> 00:52:12.500
using those patterns to drive insights, and taking those insights to your business or

00:52:12.500 --> 00:52:14.820
your organization to, like, have impact.

00:52:15.379 --> 00:52:20.020
And I just see that gray area coming up now where a lot of people kind of have the data

00:52:20.020 --> 00:52:23.060
science label, but really everything they're doing is software engineering.

00:52:23.699 --> 00:52:25.219
So – and that's fine, right?

00:52:25.219 --> 00:52:28.979
Some people might prefer the software engineering, and that's cool.

00:52:28.979 --> 00:52:30.820
They should go and do software engineering.

00:52:30.820 --> 00:52:34.020
So one of the things for you guys to think about in your career is, like, as we move

00:52:34.020 --> 00:52:38.500
towards this idea where people are asking data scientists to interact with large language

00:52:38.500 --> 00:52:43.219
models, how much of the data science part of your job are you giving up in that?

00:52:43.219 --> 00:52:47.699
And are you actually moving more towards a software engineering path in the work you're

00:52:47.699 --> 00:52:47.939
doing?

00:52:48.739 --> 00:52:50.020
And are you happy with that?

00:52:50.020 --> 00:52:53.699
And if you're not happy with that, how do you get yourself back onto the kind of data

00:52:53.699 --> 00:52:57.860
science track where you're – where I think you said it, Libby, when we connected earlier,

00:52:57.860 --> 00:53:00.899
you know, the science word, right?

00:53:00.899 --> 00:53:05.060
If you're wrangling large language models for software purposes all the time, you're

00:53:05.060 --> 00:53:06.659
not actually doing any science, right?

00:53:07.780 --> 00:53:08.739
So that's something for you.

00:53:08.739 --> 00:53:12.979
I'll leave that as a thought, a career thought for you guys to think about, I think.

00:53:12.979 --> 00:53:14.580
LIBBY GARRETT Wonderful.

00:53:14.580 --> 00:53:15.459
